ah" /><link href="http://www.dose.ca/5991413.ATOM" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" title="Movie Review: Pariah" /><entry Status="FREE"><id>tag:www.dose.ca:content=5991413</id><title type="html">Movie Review: Pariah</title><summary type="html"></summary><published>2012-01-13T00:00:00Z</published><updated>2012-01-13T16:12:03Z</updated><author><name>Katherine Monk</name></author><link href="Movie+Review+Pariah/5991413/story.html" Abstract="Dee Rees' directorial debut is a universal coming-of-age tale -- albeit one that blooms a bit slowly." Credit="Katherine Monk" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="[ more ]" /><link rel="canonical" href="http://www.dose.ca/Movie+Review+Pariah/5991413/story.html" /><link href="5991416.bin" Abstract="Pariah, Dee Rees' directorial debut, is a universal coming-of-age tale -- albeit one that blooms a bit slowly." Credit="Handout" rel="enclosure" type="image/jpeg" title="Pariah Review" /><link href="http://www.dose.ca/movies/photos/" Abstract="More Dose.ca Top 10 Lists" Credit="" rel="related" type="text/html" title="Dose.ca Top 10 Lists" /><link href="http://www.twitter.com/DoseDotCa" Abstract="Follow Dose.ca on Twitter" Credit="" rel="related" type="text/html" title="Follow Dose.ca on Twitter" /><category term="Pariah" label="ConTopic" /><category term="Postmedia News" label="Distributor" /><category term="STRY" label="ContentTypeCode" /><category term="DOSE" label="Catalog" /><category term="Y" label="Comments" /><category term="UTF8" label="Format" /><category relevance="31" term="Davis , Aasha" label="Individual" /><category relevance="18" term="Lee , Spike" label="Individual" /><category relevance="75" term="Oduye , Adepero" label="Individual" /><category relevance="100" term="Rees , Dee" label="Individual" /><category relevance="68" term="Walker , Pernell" label="Individual" /><category relevance="50" term="Wayans , Kim" label="Individual" /><category relevance="100" term="1400~Dee Rees~Adepero Oduye~Pernell Walker~Kim Wayans" label="InformQString" /><category relevance="31" term="Aasha Davis" label="Person" /><category relevance="75" term="Adepero Oduye" label="Person" /><category relevance="100" term="Dee Rees" label="Person" /><category relevance="50" term="Kim Wayans" label="Person" /><category relevance="68" term="Pernell Walker" label="Person" /><category relevance="18" term="Spike Lee" label="Person" /><category relevance="65" term="Arts, Entertainment, and Media" label="Topic" /><category relevance="65" term="Entertainment" label="Topic" /><category relevance="64" term="Movie Reviews" label="Topic" /><category relevance="65" term="Movies" label="Topic" /><content type="xhtml"><div id="1">&lt;P&gt;&lt;I&gt;This is more than a story of a young black woman coming out as a lesbian; it's a universal tale about finding yourself. Dee Rees' directorial debut may face a few challenges in the novelty department, but by the time our screen heroine Alike (Adepero Oduye) finds her moxie, the movie clicks into gear and takes us for the ride we were expecting.&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;B&gt;Starring&lt;/B&gt;: Adepero Oduye, Pernell Walker, Kim Wayans and Aasha Davis&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;B&gt;Rating&lt;/B&gt;: Three stars out of five&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Although some have snidely labelled it the lesbian Precious, there is more to Dee Rees' Pariah than a female African-American outsider facing endless challenges.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;For starters, this is not a signature slice of Oprah-endorsed entertainment. The icon partly responsible for this film's fruition is Spike Lee, a director known for craftily recreating rage and making it cinematic, as well as intellectually cogent.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Rees doesn't stew with the same sense of outsider vengeance as her film godfather who propelled her project into the limelight. Softer, quieter and far more subtle, Rees navigates a burgeoning sense of sexuality with gentle strokes.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;In the course of the opening sequence, Rees not only establishes huge chunks of character, she also outlines the central dilemma facing Alike, a young Brooklynite struggling with her identity.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Played by newcomer Adepero Oduye, Alike appears to be straddling two completely different worlds. She leaves her house wearing girlie tops and dresses, but, by the time she steps onto the curb outside her high school, she's cocooned in butch camouflage and a baseball cap.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Alike is attracted to girls, but she can't come out to her middle-class family because she's terrified of being booted from the dinner table, or worse, having a genuinely truthful discussion with her own mother (Kim Wayans).&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;The only person Alike can confide in is her best friend, Laura, played by a pitch-perfect Pernell Walker. Laura understands what Alike is going through, and offers as much support as she can muster, but she's also got her own problems to deal with.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;In fact, Laura often feels more heroic than Alike, because she's definitive, and this points out one of the central problems in Pariah: Alike feels weak.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Compared to her best friend, who already marched through the ring of fire and came out to her dysfunctional family, Alike looks awfully wishy-washy. She submits to bullying at the hands of her mother, and she sulks around the house with her shoulders hunched over, attempting to elicit sympathy by being quiet and forlorn.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;In a lot of ways, this is entirely believable teenage behaviour. But it's also undeniably irritating, especially for a central film character who has to carry the emotional weight of a rather lengthy journey to personal realization.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Compounding the problem is the unmatched potency of her mother, who dictates the terms of the family dynamic from the pulpit of maternal arrogance. There's not much tension in watching a limp noodle face off against a knife, and so, for the first act of the film, the viewer is left to swirl in Alike's wake like a bubble -- without direction, emotional heft or context.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;It's a bit of a drag, but these early scenes are saved by Walker: The newcomer has so much screen presence and natural talent, she eclipses her co-stars every time she shares the frame.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;By the time we hit the halfway mark, Alike starts to assert herself, and the story grows stronger by the second -- even as it dives headfirst into coming-of-age cliche.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;The realistic dimensions of the film -- from scope to character -- are what make Pariah worthy, not just as a piece of Sapphic Afro-Americana, but as a coming-of-age tale that hits the universals without being overtly melodramatic.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</div></content><rights type="text">Copyright (c) dose.ca</rights><source><title type="html">Movie Review: Pariah</title><subtitle type="html">Dee Rees' directorial debut is a universal coming-of-age tale -- albeit one that blooms a bit slowly.</subtitle><id>tag:www.dose.ca:content=5991413</id><rights type="html">Copyright (c) dose.ca</rights><updated>2012-01-13T16:12:03Z</updated><category term="Pariah" label="ConTopic" /><category term="Postmedia News" label="Distributor" /><category term="STRY" label="ContentTypeCode" /><category term="DOSE" label="Catalog" /><category term="Y" label="Comments" /><category term="UTF8" label="Format" /><category relevance="31" term="Davis , Aasha" label="Individual" /><category relevance="18" term="Lee , Spike" label="Individual" /><category relevance="75" term="Oduye , Adepero" label="Individual" /><category relevance="100" term="Rees , Dee" label="Individual" /><category relevance="68" term="Walker , Pernell" label="Individual" /><category relevance="50" term="Wayans , Kim" label="Individual" /><category relevance="100" term="1400~Dee Rees~Adepero Oduye~Pernell Walker~Kim Wayans" label="InformQString" /><category releva